e><gtr:surname>Weaver</gtr:surname><gtr:orcidId>0000-0001-7929-2920</gtr:orcidId><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG029482%2F1"><gtr:id>BBDB3455-7EB4-4134-8ACB-A527196F5DCA</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Rhetoric of Racist Humour: Analyzing the role of humour in racism</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G029482/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Racist humour has become the focus of argument and debate in recent times, with issues of acceptability, offence and censorship very much at the fore. Despite this, there has been little research into racist humour or the issues surrounding it. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This research provides a much needed contribution to academic and media debates on the effects of racist humour. Examining a range of case studies of racist, 'race' and ethnic humour and comedy, it is argued that, far from being an insignificant or harmless form of communication, racist humour can act as a rhetorical device for any number of discursive positions, and thus often forms a significant communicative tool for these positions. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The Fellowship will allow for the dissemination of the research findings to relevant audiences, both academic and non-academic. The overall purpose of this engagement is to provide a critical vocabulary for the analysis of humour and offence, to clarify what humour does and how it does it, and to provide a greater understanding of the role of humour in racism. &lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>59848</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Thinking allowed</gtr:description><gtr:form>A press release, press conference or response to a media enquiry/interview</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>9C6191F8-DDC2-4AF9-8A38-1B955A321868</gtr:id><gtr:impact>From Richard Pryor to Lenny Henry - how humour can reinforce or subvert racial stereotypes. The sociologist Simon Weaver tells Laurie about his research into the nature and variety of anti-racist comedy.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-5063269366.5691372b56d8a6</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Media (as a channel to the public)</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2010</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Developing a theory and method for analysing racist humour</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:id>9D9585AA-1E33-4D51-97C7-6114DE55982C</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This presentation will give a broad overview of my PhD research and how I hope to develop it during my Postdoctoral Fellowship. Outside of Loughborough there has been little research into offensive humour or the issues surrounding it. Through my research I hope to develop a theory and method for studying 'race' humour as a form of rhetoric. This presentation will discuss the approach and explain how I use linguistic models of humour to highlight how the mechanisms of humour work rhetorically, and the sociological theories of Zygmunt Bauman on the characteristics of order-building discourse in modernity and postmodernity. These ideas are applied to a number of case studies of racist humour to show how it impacts on modern and postmodern discourse. Examples from Jim Davidson and other British stand-up comedians will be used to highlight how humour sometimes reinforces the incongruities of racism, and examples from Chris Rock and other black comedians will be used to examine how humour often acts as a form of resistance.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-6433894081.44531252afdaa92</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:year>2010</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>C7B38B43-0FFB-49C1-ADEC-F8955ADFBE51</gtr:id><gtr:title>The 'Other' Laughs Back: Humour and Resistance in Anti-racist Comedy</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Sociology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/08b82a59676c03633921fd0db40d9f59"><gtr:id>08b82a59676c03633921fd0db40d9f59</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Weaver S</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cfa8fa82426773</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>F97187C5-AA8E-4248-BE9